          "reasoning": "Global mapping strategy for fixture_master_v2_src → Salesforce-style target schema.\n\nSource uses German-language identifiers with text-based natural keys. Target uses Salesforce ID convention (15/18 character IDs). Key transforms: Account IDs get 'A00' prefix, Opportunity IDs get '006' prefix, Project__c IDs get 'a1X' prefix, Contact IDs get '003' prefix, Asset IDs get 'a2X' prefix. Legacy columns preserve original source keys for row-level reconciliation.\n\nEnum domains are mapped from German source values to standardized English values (e.g., customer tiers, opportunity stages, project statuses). Dates use DD.MM.YYYY format in source — all converted to ISO YYYY-MM-DD via TO_DATE with regex guards. Amounts use European locale (dots as thousands separators, comma as decimal) — normalized before casting to DOUBLE PRECISION.\n\nAll foreign key joins use the same prefixed ID transform consistently across tables. Cross-table join columns: Contact.AccountId → Account.Id via A00 prefix; Opportunity.AccountId → Account.Id via A00 prefix; Project__c.Account__c → Account.Id via A00 prefix, Project__c.Opportunity__c → Opportunity.Id via 006 prefix; Installed_Asset__c.Account__c → Account.Id via A00 prefix, Installed_Asset__c.Project__c → Project__c.Id via a1X prefix.\nAccount is built solely from master_kunden. The natural key kundennummer is prefixed with 'A00' and uppercased to generate the Salesforce-style Id, which is then used consistently for all cross-table foreign key references (Contact.AccountId, Opportunity.AccountId, Project__c.Account__c, Installed_Asset__c.Account__c). Source text values are trimmed and normalized with INITCAP where appropriate, German customer tier synonyms (Silber/Silber → Silver, Bronce → Bronze) are mapped to the English enum domain, and URLs are lowercased with automatic https:// prefixing. Missing timestamps default to a static date since none exist in the source."
